# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: weather-forecasting-nwp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Data assimilation initially developed in the field of numerical weather prediction.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Numerical weather prediction models are equations describing the evolution of the atmosphere, typically coded into a computer program.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] When these models are used for forecasting the model output quickly deviates from the real atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Hence, we use observations of the atmosphere to keep the model on track.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Data assimilation provides a very large number of practical ways to bring these observations into the models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Simply inserting point-wise measurements into the numerical models did not provide a satisfactory solution.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Real world measurements contain errors both due to the quality of the instrument and how accurately the position of the measurement is known.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] These errors can cause instabilities in the models that eliminate any level of skill in a forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Thus, more sophisticated methods were needed in order to initialize a model using all available data while making sure to maintain stability in the numerical model.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Such data typically includes the measurements as well as a previous forecast valid at the same time the measurements are made.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] If applied iteratively, this process begins to accumulate information from past observations into all subsequent forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Because data assimilation developed out of the field of numerical weather prediction, it initially gained popularity amongst the geosciences.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] In fact, one of the most cited publication in all of the geosciences is an application of data assimilation to reconstruct the observed history of the atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Classically, data assimilation has been applied to chaotic dynamical systems that are too difficult to predict using simple extrapolation methods.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The cause of this difficulty is that small changes in initial conditions can lead to large changes in prediction accuracy.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] This is sometimes known as the butterfly effect – the sensitive dependence on initial conditions in which a small change in one state of a deterministic nonlinear system can result in large differences in a later state.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] At any update time, data assimilation usually takes a forecast (also known as the first guess, or background information) and applies a correction to the forecast based on a set of observed data and estimated errors that are present in both the observations and the forecast itself.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The difference between the forecast and the observations at that time is called the departure or the innovation (as it provides new information to the data assimilation process).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] A weighting factor is applied to the innovation to determine how much of a correction should be made to the forecast based on the new information from the observations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The best estimate of the state of the system based on the correction to the forecast determined by a weighting factor times the innovation is called the analysis.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] In one dimension, computing the analysis could be as simple as forming a weighted average of a forecasted and observed value.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] In multiple dimensions the problem becomes more difficult.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Much of the work in data assimilation is focused on adequately estimating the appropriate weighting factor based on intricate knowledge of the errors in the system.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] One of the common mathematical philosophical perspectives is to view data assimilation as a Bayesian estimation problem.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] From this perspective, the analysis step is an application of Bayes' theorem and the overall assimilation procedure is an example of recursive Bayesian estimation.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] However, the probabilistic analysis is usually simplified to a computationally feasible form.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Advancing the probability distribution in time would be done exactly in the general case by the Fokker–Planck equation, but that is not feasible for high-dimensional systems; so, various approximations operating on simplified representations of the probability distributions are used instead.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Often the probability distributions are assumed Gaussian so that they can be represented by their mean and covariance, which gives rise to the Kalman filter.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Many methods represent the probability distributions only by the mean and input some pre-calculated covariance.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] An example of a direct (or sequential) method to compute this is called optimal statistical interpolation, or simply optimal interpolation (OI).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] An alternative approach is to iteratively solve a cost function that solves an identical problem.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] These are called "variational methods", such as 3D-Var and 4D-Var.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Typical minimization algorithms are the conjugate gradient method or the generalized minimal residual method.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The ensemble Kalman filter is sequential method that uses a Monte Carlo approach to estimate both the mean and the covariance of a Gaussian probability distribution by an ensemble of simulations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] More recently, hybrid combinations of ensemble approaches and variational methods have become more popular (e.g. they are used for operational forecasts both at the European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) and at the NOAA National Centers for Environmental Prediction (NCEP).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Data assimilation can also be achieved within a model update loop, where we will iterate an initial model (or initial guess) in an optimisation loop to constrain the model to the observed data.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Many optimisation approaches exist and all of them can be set up to update the model, for instance, evolutionary algorithm have proven to be efficient as free of hypothesis, but computationally expensive.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] In numerical weather prediction applications, data assimilation is most widely known as a method for combining observations of meteorological variables such as temperature and atmospheric pressure with prior forecasts in order to initialize numerical forecast models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The idea of numerical weather prediction is to sample the state of the fluid at a given time and use the equations of fluid dynamics and thermodynamics to estimate the state of the fluid at some time in the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The process of entering observation data into the model to generate initial conditions is called *initialization*.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The main inputs from country-based weather services are observations from devices (called radiosondes) in weather balloons that measure various atmospheric parameters and transmits them to a fixed receiver, as well as from weather satellites.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The World Meteorological Organization acts to standardize the instrumentation, observing practices and timing of these observations worldwide.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Stations either report hourly in METAR reports, or every six hours in SYNOP reports.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] These observations are irregularly spaced, so they are processed by data assimilation and objective analysis methods, which perform quality control and obtain values at locations usable by the model's mathematical algorithms.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Some global models use finite differences, in which the world is represented as discrete points on a regularly spaced grid of latitude and longitude; other models use spectral methods that solve for a range of wavelengths.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The data are then used in the model as the starting point for a forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] A variety of methods are used to gather observational data for use in numerical models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Sites launch radiosondes in weather balloons which rise through the troposphere and well into the stratosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Information from weather satellites is used where traditional data sources are not available.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Commerce provides pilot reports along aircraft routes and ship reports along shipping routes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Research projects use reconnaissance aircraft to fly in and around weather systems of interest, such as tropical cyclones.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Reconnaissance aircraft are also flown over the open oceans during the cold season into systems which cause significant uncertainty in forecast guidance, or are expected to be of high impact from three to seven days into the future over the downstream continent.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Sea ice began to be initialized in forecast models in 1971.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Efforts to involve sea surface temperature in model initialization began in 1972 due to its role in modulating weather in higher latitudes of the Pacific.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] In 1922, Lewis Fry Richardson published the first attempt at forecasting the weather numerically.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Using a hydrostatic variation of Bjerknes's primitive equations, Richardson produced by hand a 6-hour forecast for the state of the atmosphere over two points in central Europe, taking at least six weeks to do so.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] His forecast calculated that the change in surface pressure would be 145 millibars (4.3 inHg), an unrealistic value incorrect by two orders of magnitude.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The large error was caused by an imbalance in the pressure and wind velocity fields used as the initial conditions in his analysis, indicating the need for a data assimilation scheme.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Originally "subjective analysis" had been used in which numerical weather prediction (NWP) forecasts had been adjusted by meteorologists using their operational expertise.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Cressman algorithm) was introduced for automated data assimilation.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] These objective methods used simple interpolation approaches, and thus were 3DDA (three-dimensional data assimilation) methods.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Later, 4DDA (four-dimensional data assimilation) methods, called "nudging", were developed, such as in the MM5 model.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] They are based on the simple idea of Newtonian relaxation (the 2nd axiom of Newton).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] They introduce into the right part of dynamical equations of the model a term that is proportional to the difference of the calculated meteorological variable and the observed value.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] This term that has a negative sign keeps the calculated state vector closer to the observations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Nudging can be interpreted as a variant of the Kalman-Bucy filter (a continuous time version of the Kalman filter) with the gain matrix prescribed rather than obtained from covariances.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Gandin (1963) who introduced the "statistical interpolation" (or "optimal interpolation") method, which developed earlier ideas of Kolmogorov.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] This is a 3DDA method and is a type of regression analysis which utilizes information about the spatial distributions of covariance functions of the errors of the "first guess" field (previous forecast) and "true field".
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] However, the different approximations were assumed.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The optimal interpolation algorithm is the reduced version of the Kalman filtering (KF) algorithm and in which the covariance matrices are not calculated from the dynamical equations but are pre-determined in advance.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Attempts to introduce the KF algorithms as a 4DDA tool for NWP models came later.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] However, this was (and remains) a difficult task because the full version requires solution of the enormous number of additional equations (~N*N~10**12, where N=Nx*Ny*Nz is the size of the state vector, Nx~100, Ny~100, Nz~100 – the dimensions of the computational grid).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] To overcome this difficulty, approximate or suboptimal Kalman filters were developed.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] These include the Ensemble Kalman filter and the Reduced-Rank Kalman filters (RRSQRT).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Another significant advance in the development of the 4DDA methods was utilizing the optimal control theory (variational approach) in the works of Le Dimet and Talagrand (1986), based on the previous works of J.-L.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Marchuk, the latter being the first to apply that theory in the environmental modeling.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The significant advantage of the variational approaches is that the meteorological fields satisfy the dynamical equations of the NWP model and at the same time they minimize the functional, characterizing their difference from observations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Thus, the problem of constrained minimization is solved.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The 3DDA variational methods were developed for the first time by Sasaki (1958).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] As was shown by Lorenc (1986), all the above-mentioned 4DDA methods are in some limit equivalent, i.e. under some assumptions they minimize the same cost function.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] However, in practical applications these assumptions are never fulfilled, the different methods perform differently and generally it is not clear what approach (Kalman filtering or variational) is better.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The fundamental questions also arise in application of the advanced DA techniques such as convergence of the computational method to the global minimum of the functional to be minimised.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] For instance, cost function or the set in which the solution is sought can be not convex.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] This data assimilation method is used operationally at forecast centres such as the Met Office.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The process of creating the analysis in data assimilation often involves minimization of a cost function.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] A typical cost function would be the sum of the squared deviations of the analysis values from the observations weighted by the accuracy of the observations, plus the sum of the squared deviations of the forecast fields and the analyzed fields weighted by the accuracy of the forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] This has the effect of making sure that the analysis does not drift too far away from observations and forecasts that are known to usually be reliable.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] where $\mathbf {B}$ denotes the background error covariance, $\mathbf {R}$ the observational error covariance.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] provided that ${\mathit {H}}$ is a linear operator (matrix).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Data assimilation has been used, in the 1980s and 1990s, in several HAPEX (Hydrologic and Atmospheric Pilot Experiment) projects for monitoring energy transfers between the soil, vegetation and atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Data assimilation methods are currently also used in other environmental forecasting problems, e.g. in hydrological and hydrogeological forecasting.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Bayesian networks may also be used in a data assimilation approach to assess natural hazards such as landslides.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Given the abundance of spacecraft data for other planets in the Solar System, data assimilation is now also applied beyond the Earth to obtain re-analyses of the atmospheric state of extraterrestrial planets.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Mars is the only extraterrestrial planet to which data assimilation has been applied so far.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Available spacecraft data include, in particular, retrievals of temperature and dust/water/ice optical thicknesses from the Thermal Emission Spectrometer onboard NASA's Mars Global Surveyor and the Mars Climate Sounder onboard NASA's Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Two methods of data assimilation have been applied to these datasets: an Analysis Correction scheme and two Ensemble Kalman Filter schemes, both using a global circulation model of the martian atmosphere as forward model.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The Mars Analysis Correction Data Assimilation (MACDA) dataset is publicly available from the British Atmospheric Data Centre.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Data assimilation is a part of the challenge for every forecasting problem.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Dealing with biased data is a serious challenge in data assimilation.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Further development of methods to deal with biases will be of particular use.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] If there are several instruments observing the same variable then intercomparing them using probability distribution functions can be instructive.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] This increase in horizontal resolutions is starting to allow to resolve more chaotic features of the non-linear models, e.g. to resolve convection on the grid scale, or clouds, in the atmospheric models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] This increasing non-linearity in the models and observation operators poses a new problem in the data assimilation.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] The existing data assimilation methods such as many variants of ensemble Kalman filters and variational methods, well established with linear or near-linear models, are being assessed on non-linear models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Many new methods are being developed, e.g. particle filters for high-dimensional problems, and hybrid data assimilation methods.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/data-assimilation] Other uses include trajectory estimation for the Apollo program, GPS, and atmospheric chemistry.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Ensemble forecasting is a form of Monte Carlo analysis.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Ideally, the verified future atmospheric state should fall within the predicted ensemble spread, and the amount of spread should be related to the uncertainty (error) of the forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] In general, this approach can be used to make probabilistic forecasts of any dynamical system, and not just for weather prediction.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Experimental ensemble forecasts are made at a number of universities, such as the University of Washington, and ensemble forecasts in the US are also generated by the US Navy and Air Force.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] There are various ways of viewing the data such as spaghetti plots, *ensemble means* or *Postage Stamps* where a number of different results from the models run can be compared.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] As proposed by Edward Lorenz in 1963, it is impossible for long-range forecasts—those made more than two weeks in advance—to predict the state of the atmosphere with any degree of skill owing to the chaotic nature of the fluid dynamics equations involved.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Furthermore, existing observation networks have limited spatial and temporal resolution (for example, over large bodies of water such as the Pacific Ocean), which introduces uncertainty into the true initial state of the atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] While a set of equations, known as the Liouville equations, exists to determine the initial uncertainty in the model initialization, the equations are too complex to run in real-time, even with the use of supercomputers.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The practical importance of ensemble forecasts derives from the fact that in a chaotic and hence nonlinear system, the rate of growth of forecast error is dependent on starting conditions.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] An ensemble forecast therefore provides a prior estimate of state-dependent predictability, i.e. an estimate of the types of weather that might occur, given inevitable uncertainties in the forecast initial conditions and in the accuracy of the computational representation of the equations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] These uncertainties limit forecast model accuracy to about six days into the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The first operational ensemble forecasts were produced for sub-seasonal timescales in 1985.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] However, it was realised that the philosophy underpinning such forecasts was also relevant on shorter timescales – timescales where predictions had previously been made by purely deterministic means.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Edward Epstein recognized in 1969 that the atmosphere could not be completely described with a single forecast run due to inherent uncertainty, and proposed a stochastic dynamic model that produced means and variances for the state of the atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Although these Monte Carlo simulations showed skill, in 1974 Cecil Leith revealed that they produced adequate forecasts only when the ensemble probability distribution was a representative sample of the probability distribution in the atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] It was not until 1992 that ensemble forecasts began being prepared by the European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) and the National Centers for Environmental Prediction (NCEP).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] There are two main sources of uncertainty that must be accounted for when making an ensemble weather forecast: initial condition uncertainty and model uncertainty.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Initial condition uncertainty arises due to errors in the estimate of the starting conditions for the forecast, both due to limited observations of the atmosphere, and uncertainties involved in using indirect measurements, such as satellite data, to measure the state of atmospheric variables.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Initial condition uncertainty is represented by perturbing the starting conditions between the different ensemble members.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] This explores the range of starting conditions consistent with our knowledge of the current state of the atmosphere, together with its past evolution.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] There are a number of ways to generate these initial condition perturbations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The ECMWF model, the Ensemble Prediction System (EPS), uses a combination of singular vectors and an ensemble of data assimilations (EDA) to simulate the initial probability density.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The singular vector perturbations are more active in the extra-tropics, while the EDA perturbations are more active in the tropics.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The NCEP ensemble, the Global Ensemble Forecasting System, uses a technique known as vector breeding.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Perturbing the initial state from the satellite measurements such that the perturbed states look physical is a tough task.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Also, deep learning has brought forward some techniques to perturb the complex initial state almost physically using flow matching.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Model uncertainty arises due to the limitations of the forecast model.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The process of representing the atmosphere in a computer model involves many simplifications such as the development of parametrisation schemes, which introduce errors into the forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Several techniques to represent model uncertainty have been proposed.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] When developing a parametrisation scheme, many new parameters are introduced to represent simplified physical processes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] For example, the 'entrainment coefficient' represents the turbulent mixing of dry environmental air into a convective cloud, and so represents a complex physical process using a single number.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] In a perturbed parameter approach, uncertain parameters in the model's parametrisation schemes are identified and their value changed between ensemble members.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] While in probabilistic climate modelling, such as climateprediction.net, these parameters are often held constant globally and throughout the integration, in modern numerical weather prediction it is more common to stochastically vary the value of the parameters in time and space.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The degree of parameter perturbation can be guided using expert judgement, or by directly estimating the degree of parameter uncertainty for a given model.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] A traditional parametrisation scheme seeks to represent the average effect of the sub grid-scale motion (e.g. convective clouds) on the resolved scale state (e.g. the large scale temperature and wind fields).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] A stochastic parametrisation scheme recognises that there may be many sub-grid scale states consistent with a particular resolved scale state.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Instead of predicting the most likely sub-grid scale motion, a stochastic parametrisation scheme represents one possible realisation of the sub-grid.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] It does this through including random numbers into the equations of motion.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] This samples from the probability distribution assigned to uncertain processes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Stochastic parametrisations have significantly improved the skill of weather forecasting models, and are now used in operational forecasting centres worldwide.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Stochastic parametrisations were first developed at the European Centre for Medium Range Weather Forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] When many different forecast models are used to try to generate a forecast, the approach is termed multi-model ensemble forecasting.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] This method of forecasting can improve forecasts when compared to a single model-based approach.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] When the models within a multi-model ensemble are adjusted for their various biases, this process is known as "superensemble forecasting".
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] This type of a forecast significantly reduces errors in model output.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] When models of different physical processes are combined, such as combinations of atmospheric, ocean and wave models, the multi-model ensemble is called hyper-ensemble.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The ensemble forecast is usually evaluated by comparing the ensemble average of the individual forecasts for one forecast variable to the observed value of that variable (the "error").
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] This is combined with consideration of the degree of agreement between various forecasts within the ensemble system, as represented by their overall standard deviation or "spread".
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Ensemble spread can be visualised through tools such as spaghetti diagrams, which show the dispersion of one quantity on prognostic charts for specific time steps in the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Another tool where ensemble spread is used is a meteogram, which shows the dispersion in the forecast of one quantity for one specific location.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] It is common for the ensemble spread to be too small, such that the observed atmospheric state falls outside of the ensemble forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] This can lead the forecaster to be overconfident in their forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] This problem becomes particularly severe for forecasts of the weather about 10 days in advance, particularly if model uncertainty is not accounted for in the forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The spread of the ensemble forecast indicates how confident the forecaster can be in his or her prediction.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] When ensemble spread is small and the forecast solutions are consistent within multiple model runs, forecasters perceive more confidence in the forecast in general.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] When the spread is large, this indicates more uncertainty in the prediction.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Ideally, a *spread-skill relationship* should exist, whereby the spread of the ensemble is a good predictor of the expected error in the ensemble mean.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] If the forecast is *reliable,* the observed state will behave as if it is drawn from the forecast probability distribution.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Reliability (or *calibration*) can be evaluated by comparing the standard deviation of the error in the ensemble mean with the forecast spread: for a reliable forecast, the two should match, both at different forecast lead times and for different locations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The reliability of forecasts of a specific weather event can also be assessed.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] For example, if 30 of 50 members indicated greater than 1 cm rainfall during the next 24 h, the probability of exceeding 1 cm could be estimated to be 60%.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The forecast would be considered reliable if, considering all the situations in the past when a 60% probability was forecast, on 60% of those occasions did the rainfall actually exceed 1 cm.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] In practice, the probabilities generated from operational weather ensemble forecasts are not highly reliable, though with a set of past forecasts (*reforecasts* or *hindcasts*) and observations, the probability estimates from the ensemble can be adjusted to ensure greater reliability.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Another desirable property of ensemble forecasts is *resolution.* This is an indication of how much the forecast deviates from the climatological event frequency – provided that the ensemble is reliable, increasing this deviation will increase the usefulness of the forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] This forecast quality can also be considered in terms of *sharpness*, or how small the spread of the forecast is.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The key aim of a forecaster should be to maximise sharpness, while maintaining reliability.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] If ensemble forecasts are to be used for predicting probabilities of observed weather variables they typically need calibration in order to create unbiased and reliable forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] For forecasts of temperature one simple and effective method of calibration is linear regression, often known in this context as model output statistics.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The linear regression model takes the ensemble mean as a predictor for the real temperature, ignores the distribution of ensemble members around the mean, and predicts probabilities using the distribution of residuals from the regression.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] This proved for the first time that information in the shape of the distribution of the members of an ensemble around the mean, in this case summarized by the ensemble spread, can be used to improve forecasts relative to linear regression.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Whether or not linear regression can be beaten by using the ensemble spread in this way varies, depending on the forecast system, forecast variable and lead time.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] In addition to being used to improve predictions of uncertainty, the ensemble spread can also be used as a predictor for the likely size of changes in the mean forecast from one forecast to the next.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] This works because, in some ensemble forecast systems, narrow ensembles tend to precede small changes in the mean, while wide ensembles tend to precede larger changes in the mean.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] This has applications in the trading industries, for whom understanding the likely sizes of future forecast changes can be important.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] The Observing System Research and Predictability Experiment (THORPEX) is a 10-year international research and development programme to accelerate improvements in the accuracy of one-day to two-week high impact weather forecasts for the benefit of society, the economy and the environment.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] It establishes an organizational framework that addresses weather research and forecast problems whose solutions will be accelerated through international collaboration among academic institutions, operational forecast centres and users of forecast products.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] One of its key components is THORPEX Interactive Grand Global Ensemble (TIGGE), a World Weather Research Programme to accelerate the improvements in the accuracy of 1-day to 2 week high-impact weather forecasts for the benefit of humanity.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/ensemble-forecasting] Centralized archives of ensemble model forecast data, from many international centers, are used to enable extensive data sharing and research.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Mathematical models based on the same physical principles can be used to generate either short-term weather forecasts or longer-term climate predictions; the latter are widely applied for understanding and projecting climate change.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The improvements made to regional models have allowed significant improvements in tropical cyclone track and air quality forecasts; however, atmospheric models perform poorly at handling processes that occur in a relatively constricted area, such as wildfires.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Manipulating the vast datasets and performing the complex calculations necessary to modern numerical weather prediction requires some of the most powerful supercomputers in the world.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Even with the increasing power of supercomputers, the forecast skill of numerical weather models extends to only about six days.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Factors affecting the accuracy of numerical predictions include the density and quality of observations used as input to the forecasts, along with deficiencies in the numerical models themselves.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Post-processing techniques such as model output statistics (MOS) have been developed to improve the handling of errors in numerical predictions.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] A more fundamental problem lies in the chaotic nature of the partial differential equations that describe the atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] It is impossible to solve these equations exactly, and small errors grow with time (doubling about every five days).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Present understanding is that this chaotic behavior limits accurate forecasts to about 14 days even with accurate input data and a flawless model.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] In addition, the partial differential equations used in the model need to be supplemented with parameterizations for solar radiation, moist processes (clouds and precipitation), heat exchange, soil, vegetation, surface water, and the effects of terrain.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] In an effort to quantify the large amount of inherent uncertainty remaining in numerical predictions, ensemble forecasts have been used since the 1990s to help gauge the confidence in the forecast, and to obtain useful results farther into the future than otherwise possible.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] This approach analyzes multiple forecasts created with an individual forecast model or multiple models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] It was not until the advent of the computer and computer simulations that computation time was reduced to less than the forecast period itself.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The ENIAC was used to create the first weather forecasts via computer in 1950, based on a highly simplified approximation to the atmospheric governing equations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] In 1954, Carl-Gustav Rossby's group at the Swedish Meteorological and Hydrological Institute used the same model to produce the first operational forecast (i.e., a routine prediction for practical use).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Operational numerical weather prediction in the United States began in 1955 under the Joint Numerical Weather Prediction Unit (JNWPU), a joint project by the U.S.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] In 1956, Norman Phillips developed a mathematical model which could realistically depict monthly and seasonal patterns in the troposphere; this became the first successful climate model.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Following Phillips' work, several groups began working to create general circulation models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The first general circulation climate model that combined both oceanic and atmospheric processes was developed in the late 1960s at the NOAA Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] As computers have become more powerful, the size of the initial data sets has increased and newer atmospheric models have been developed to take advantage of the added available computing power.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] These newer models include more physical processes in the simplifications of the equations of motion in numerical simulations of the atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] In 1966, West Germany and the United States began producing operational forecasts based on primitive-equation models, followed by the United Kingdom in 1972 and Australia in 1977.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The development of limited area (regional) models facilitated advances in forecasting the tracks of tropical cyclones as well as air quality in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] By the early 1980s models began to include the interactions of soil and vegetation with the atmosphere, which led to more realistic forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The output of forecast models based on atmospheric dynamics is unable to resolve some details of the weather near the Earth's surface.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] As such, a statistical relationship between the output of a numerical weather model and the ensuing conditions at the ground was developed in the 1970s and 1980s, known as model output statistics (MOS).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Starting in the 1990s, model ensemble forecasts have been used to help define the forecast uncertainty and to extend the window in which numerical weather forecasting is viable farther into the future than otherwise possible.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] As such, the idea of numerical weather prediction is to sample the state of the fluid at a given time and use the equations of fluid dynamics and thermodynamics to estimate the state of the fluid at some time in the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] One main source of input is observations from devices (called radiosondes) in weather balloons which rise through the troposphere and well into the stratosphere that measure various atmospheric parameters and transmits them to a fixed receiver.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Another main input is data from weather satellites.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Commercial aircraft provide pilot reports along travel routes and ship reports along shipping routes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Commercial aircraft also submit automatic reports via the WMO's Aircraft Meteorological Data Relay (AMDAR) system, using VHF radio to ground stations or satellites.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] An atmospheric model is a computer program that produces meteorological information for future times at given locations and altitudes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Within any modern model is a set of equations, known as the primitive equations, used to predict the future state of the atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] These equations—along with the ideal gas law—are used to evolve the density, pressure, and potential temperature scalar fields and the air velocity (wind) vector field of the atmosphere through time.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Additional transport equations for pollutants and other aerosols are included in some primitive-equation high-resolution models as well.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The equations used are nonlinear partial differential equations which are impossible to solve exactly through analytical methods, with the exception of a few idealized cases.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Therefore, numerical methods obtain approximate solutions.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] These equations are initialized from the analysis data and rates of change are determined.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] These rates of change predict the state of the atmosphere a short time into the future; the time increment for this prediction is called a *time step*.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] This future atmospheric state is then used as the starting point for another application of the predictive equations to find new rates of change, and these new rates of change predict the atmosphere at a yet further time step into the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] This time stepping is repeated until the solution reaches the desired forecast time.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The length of the time step chosen within the model is related to the distance between the points on the computational grid, and is chosen to maintain numerical stability.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Time steps for global models are on the order of tens of minutes, while time steps for regional models are between one and four minutes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The global models are run at varying times into the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The visual output produced by a model solution is known as a prognostic chart, or *prog*.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Some meteorological processes are too small-scale or too complex to be explicitly included in numerical weather prediction models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] *Parameterization* is a procedure for representing these processes by relating them to variables on the scales that the model resolves.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] For example, the gridboxes in weather and climate models have sides that are between 5 kilometers (3 mi) and 300 kilometers (200 mi) in length.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] A typical cumulus cloud has a scale of less than 1 kilometer (0.6 mi), and would require a grid even finer than this to be represented physically by the equations of fluid motion.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Therefore, the processes that such clouds represent are parameterized, by processes of various sophistication.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] More sophisticated schemes recognize that only some portions of the box might convect and that entrainment and other processes occur.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Weather models that have gridboxes with sizes between 5 and 25 kilometers (3 and 16 mi) can explicitly represent convective clouds, although they need to parameterize cloud microphysics which occur at a smaller scale.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The formation of large-scale (stratus-type) clouds is more physically based; they form when the relative humidity reaches some prescribed value.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The cloud fraction can be related to this critical value of relative humidity.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The amount of solar radiation reaching the ground, as well as the formation of cloud droplets occur on the molecular scale, and so they must be parameterized before they can be included in the model.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Atmospheric drag produced by mountains must also be parameterized, as the limitations in the resolution of elevation contours produce significant underestimates of the drag.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] This method of parameterization is also done for the surface flux of energy between the ocean and the atmosphere, in order to determine realistic sea surface temperatures and type of sea ice found near the ocean's surface.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Sun angle as well as the impact of multiple cloud layers is taken into account.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Soil type, vegetation type, and soil moisture all determine how much radiation goes into warming and how much moisture is drawn up into the adjacent atmosphere, and thus it is important to parameterize their contribution to these processes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Within air quality models, parameterizations take into account atmospheric emissions from multiple relatively tiny sources (e.g. roads, fields, factories) within specific grid boxes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The horizontal domain of a model is either *global*, covering the entire Earth, or *regional*, covering only part of the Earth.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Regional models (also known as *limited-area* models, or LAMs) allow for the use of finer grid spacing than global models because the available computational resources are focused on a specific area instead of being spread over the globe.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] This allows regional models to resolve explicitly smaller-scale meteorological phenomena that cannot be represented on the coarser grid of a global model.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Regional models use a global model to specify conditions at the edge of their domain (boundary conditions) in order to allow systems from outside the regional model domain to move into its area.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Uncertainty and errors within regional models are introduced by the global model used for the boundary conditions of the edge of the regional model, as well as errors attributable to the regional model itself.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The vertical coordinate is handled in various ways.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Lewis Fry Richardson's 1922 model used geometric height ( z ) as the vertical coordinate.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Later models substituted the geometric z coordinate with a pressure coordinate system, in which the geopotential heights of constant-pressure surfaces become dependent variables, greatly simplifying the primitive equations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] This correlation between coordinate systems can be made since pressure decreases with height through the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The first model used for operational forecasts, the single-layer barotropic model, used a single pressure coordinate at the 500-millibar (about 5,500 m (18,000 ft)) level, and thus was essentially two-dimensional.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] High-resolution models—also called *mesoscale models*—such as the Weather Research and Forecasting model tend to use normalized pressure coordinates referred to as sigma coordinates.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] This coordinate system receives its name from the independent variable $\sigma$ used to scale atmospheric pressures with respect to the pressure at the surface, and in some cases also with the pressure at the top of the domain.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Because forecast models based upon the equations for atmospheric dynamics do not perfectly determine weather conditions, statistical methods have been developed to attempt to correct the forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Statistical models were created based upon the three-dimensional fields produced by numerical weather models, surface observations and the climatological conditions for specific locations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] These statistical models are collectively referred to as model output statistics (MOS), and were developed by the National Weather Service for their suite of weather forecasting models in the late 1960s.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Model output statistics differ from the *perfect prog* technique, which assumes that the output of numerical weather prediction guidance is perfect.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] MOS can correct for local effects that cannot be resolved by the model due to insufficient grid resolution, as well as model biases.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Because MOS is run after its respective global or regional model, its production is known as post-processing.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Forecast parameters within MOS include maximum and minimum temperatures, percentage chance of rain within a several hour period, precipitation amount expected, chance that the precipitation will be frozen in nature, chance for thunderstorms, cloudiness, and surface winds.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] In 1963, Edward Lorenz discovered the chaotic nature of the fluid dynamics equations involved in weather forecasting.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Extremely small errors in temperature, winds, or other initial inputs given to numerical models will amplify and double every five days, making it impossible for long-range forecasts—those made more than two weeks in advance—to predict the state of the atmosphere with any degree of forecast skill.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Furthermore, existing observation networks have poor coverage in some regions (for example, over large bodies of water such as the Pacific Ocean), which introduces uncertainty into the true initial state of the atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] These uncertainties limit forecast model accuracy to about five or six days into the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Edward Epstein recognized in 1969 that the atmosphere could not be completely described with a single forecast run due to inherent uncertainty, and proposed using an ensemble of stochastic Monte Carlo simulations to produce means and variances for the state of the atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Although this early example of an ensemble showed skill, in 1974 Cecil Leith showed that they produced adequate forecasts only when the ensemble probability distribution was a representative sample of the probability distribution in the atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Since the 1990s, *ensemble forecasts* have been used operationally (as routine forecasts) to account for the stochastic nature of weather processes – that is, to resolve their inherent uncertainty.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] This method involves analyzing multiple forecasts created with an individual forecast model by using different physical parametrizations or varying initial conditions.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The ECMWF model, the Ensemble Prediction System, uses singular vectors to simulate the initial probability density, while the NCEP ensemble, the Global Ensemble Forecasting System, uses a technique known as vector breeding.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The UK Met Office runs global and regional ensemble forecasts where perturbations to initial conditions are used by 24 ensemble members in the Met Office Global and Regional Ensemble Prediction System (MOGREPS) to produce 24 different forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] In a single model-based approach, the ensemble forecast is usually evaluated in terms of an average of the individual forecasts concerning one forecast variable, as well as the degree of agreement between various forecasts within the ensemble system, as represented by their overall spread.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Ensemble spread is diagnosed through tools such as spaghetti diagrams, which show the dispersion of one quantity on prognostic charts for specific time steps in the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] It is common for the ensemble spread to be too small to include the weather that actually occurs, which can lead to forecasters misdiagnosing model uncertainty; this problem becomes particularly severe for forecasts of the weather about ten days in advance.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] When ensemble spread is small and the forecast solutions are consistent within multiple model runs, forecasters perceive more confidence in the ensemble mean, and the forecast in general.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Despite this perception, a *spread-skill relationship* is often weak or not found, as spread-error correlations are normally less than 0.6, and only under special circumstances range between 0.6–0.7.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The relationship between ensemble spread and forecast skill varies substantially depending on such factors as the forecast model and the region for which the forecast is made.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] In the same way that many forecasts from a single model can be used to form an ensemble, multiple models may also be combined to produce an ensemble forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] This approach is called *multi-model ensemble forecasting*, and it has been shown to improve forecasts when compared to a single model-based approach.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Models within a multi-model ensemble can be adjusted for their various biases, which is a process known as *superensemble forecasting*.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] This type of forecast significantly reduces errors in model output.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Air quality forecasting attempts to predict when the concentrations of pollutants will attain levels that are hazardous to public health.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The concentration of pollutants in the atmosphere is determined by their *transport*, or mean velocity of movement through the atmosphere, their diffusion, chemical transformation, and ground deposition.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] In addition to pollutant source and terrain information, these models require data about the state of the fluid flow in the atmosphere to determine its transport and diffusion.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Meteorological conditions such as thermal inversions can prevent surface air from rising, trapping pollutants near the surface, which makes accurate forecasts of such events crucial for air quality modeling.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Urban air quality models require a very fine computational mesh, requiring the use of high-resolution mesoscale weather models; in spite of this, the quality of numerical weather guidance is the main uncertainty in air quality forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] A General Circulation Model (GCM) is a mathematical model that can be used in computer simulations of the global circulation of a planetary atmosphere or ocean.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] An atmospheric general circulation model (AGCM) is essentially the same as a global numerical weather prediction model, and some (such as the one used in the UK Unified Model) can be configured for both short-term weather forecasts and longer-term climate predictions.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Along with sea ice and land-surface components, AGCMs and oceanic GCMs (OGCM) are key components of global climate models, and are widely applied for understanding the climate and projecting climate change.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] For aspects of climate change, a range of man-made chemical emission scenarios can be fed into the climate models to see how an enhanced greenhouse effect would modify the Earth's climate.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Versions designed for climate applications with time scales of decades to centuries were originally created in 1969 by Syukuro Manabe and Kirk Bryan at the Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] When run for multiple decades, computational limitations mean that the models must use a coarse grid that leaves smaller-scale interactions unresolved.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The transfer of energy between the wind blowing over the surface of an ocean and the ocean's upper layer is an important element in wave dynamics.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The spectral wave transport equation is used to describe the change in wave spectrum over changing topography.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] It simulates wave generation, wave movement (propagation within a fluid), wave shoaling, refraction, energy transfer between waves, and wave dissipation.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Since surface winds are the primary forcing mechanism in the spectral wave transport equation, ocean wave models use information produced by numerical weather prediction models as inputs to determine how much energy is transferred from the atmosphere into the layer at the surface of the ocean.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Along with dissipation of energy through whitecaps and resonance between waves, surface winds from numerical weather models allow for more accurate predictions of the state of the sea surface.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Tropical cyclone forecasting also relies on data provided by numerical weather models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Three main classes of tropical cyclone guidance models exist: Statistical models are based on an analysis of storm behavior using climatology, and correlate a storm's position and date to produce a forecast that is not based on the physics of the atmosphere at the time.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Models that use elements of both approaches are called statistical-dynamical models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] In 1978, the first hurricane-tracking model based on atmospheric dynamics—the movable fine-mesh (MFM) model—began operating.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Predictions of the intensity of a tropical cyclone based on numerical weather prediction continue to be a challenge, since statistical methods continue to show higher skill over dynamical guidance.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Because weather drifts across the world, producing forecasts a week or more in advance typically involves running a numerical prediction model for the entire planet.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The global models can be used to supply boundary conditions to higher-resolution models that provide more accurate forecasts for an area of interest, such as the country served by a government agency, or an area where military action or rescue efforts are planned.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The output of higher-resolution models may be further modified by model output statistics to take into quirky local phenomena that general models do not handle well, such as mountain waves.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] On a molecular scale, there are two main competing reaction processes involved in the degradation of cellulose, or wood fuels, in wildfires.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] When there is a low amount of moisture in a cellulose fiber, volatilization of the fuel occurs; this process will generate intermediate gaseous products that will ultimately be the source of combustion.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] When moisture is present—or when enough heat is being carried away from the fiber, charring occurs.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The chemical kinetics of both reactions indicate that there is a point at which the level of moisture is low enough—and/or heating rates high enough—for combustion processes to become self-sufficient.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Consequently, changes in wind speed, direction, moisture, temperature, or lapse rate at different levels of the atmosphere can have a significant impact on the behavior and growth of a wildfire.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] Since the wildfire acts as a heat source to the atmospheric flow, the wildfire can modify local advection patterns, introducing a feedback loop between the fire and the atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] A simplified two-dimensional model for the spread of wildfires that used convection to represent the effects of wind and terrain, as well as radiative heat transfer as the dominant method of heat transport led to reaction–diffusion systems of partial differential equations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] More complex models join numerical weather models or computational fluid dynamics models with a wildfire component which allow the feedback effects between the fire and the atmosphere to be estimated.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] The additional complexity in the latter class of models translates to a corresponding increase in their computer power requirements.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/numerical-weather-prediction] In fact, a full three-dimensional treatment of combustion via direct numerical simulation at scales relevant for atmospheric modeling is not currently practical because of the excessive computational cost such a simulation would require.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The **primitive equations** are a set of nonlinear partial differential equations that are used to approximate global atmospheric flow and are used in most atmospheric models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The primitive equations may be linearized to yield Laplace's tidal equations, an eigenvalue problem from which the analytical solution to the latitudinal structure of the flow may be determined.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] In general, nearly all forms of the primitive equations relate the five variables *u*, *v*, ω, *T*, *W*, and their evolution over space and time.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The equations were first written down by Vilhelm Bjerknes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] Forces that cause atmospheric motion include the pressure gradient force, gravity, and viscous friction.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] Together, they create the forces that accelerate our atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The pressure gradient force causes an acceleration forcing air from regions of high pressure to regions of low pressure.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The gravitational force accelerates objects at approximately 9.8 m/s2 directly towards the center of the Earth.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] Using Newton's second law, these forces (referenced in the equations above as the accelerations due to these forces) may be summed to produce an equation of motion that describes this system.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] where n is the number density in mol, and T:=RT is the temperature equivalent value in Joule/mol.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The precise form of the primitive equations depends on the vertical coordinate system chosen, such as pressure coordinates, log pressure coordinates, or sigma coordinates.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] Furthermore, the velocity, temperature, and geopotential variables may be decomposed into mean and perturbation components using Reynolds decomposition.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] In this form pressure is selected as the vertical coordinate and the horizontal coordinates are written for the Cartesian tangential plane (i.e. a plane tangent to some point on the surface of the Earth).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] This form does not take the curvature of the Earth into account, but is useful for visualizing some of the physical processes involved in formulating the equations due to its relative simplicity.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] Note that the capital D time derivatives are material derivatives.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] Five equations in five unknowns comprise the system.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] When a statement of the conservation of water vapor substance is included, these six equations can form the basis for a numerical weather prediction scheme.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] According to the *National Weather Service Handbook No.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The first term is equal to the change in temperature due to incoming solar radiation and outgoing longwave radiation, which changes with time throughout the day.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The second, third, and fourth terms are due to advection.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] Additionally, the variable *T* with subscript is the change in temperature on that plane.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] Each *T* is actually different and related to its respective plane.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] This is divided by the distance between grid points to get the change in temperature with the change in distance.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] When multiplied by the wind velocity on that plane, the units kelvins per meter and meters per second give kelvins per second.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The sum of all the changes in temperature due to motions in the *x*, *y*, and *z* directions give the total change in temperature with time.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] This equation and notation works in much the same way as the temperature equation.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] This equation describes the motion of water from one place to another at a point without taking into account water that changes form.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] Inside a given system, the total change in water with time is zero.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] However, concentrations are allowed to move with the wind.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] These simplifications make it much easier to understand what is happening in the model.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] Things like the temperature (potential temperature), precipitable water, and to an extent the pressure thickness simply move from one spot on the grid to another with the wind.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The wind is forecast slightly differently.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] It uses geopotential, specific heat, the Exner function *π*, and change in sigma coordinate.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The analytic solution to the linearized primitive equations involves a sinusoidal oscillation in time and longitude, modulated by coefficients related to height and latitude.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] where *s* and $\sigma$ are the zonal wavenumber and angular frequency, respectively.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] The solution represents atmospheric waves and tides.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] When the coefficients are separated into their height and latitude components, the height dependence takes the form of propagating or evanescent waves (depending on conditions), while the latitude dependence is given by the Hough functions.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] This analytic solution is only possible when the primitive equations are linearized and simplified.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] Unfortunately many of these simplifications (i.e. no dissipation, isothermal atmosphere) do not correspond to conditions in the actual atmosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/primitive-equations] As a result, a numerical solution which takes these factors into account is often calculated using general circulation models and climate models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Consequently, spectral methods connect variables *globally* while finite elements do so *locally*.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Partially for this reason, spectral methods have excellent error properties, with the so-called "exponential convergence" being the fastest possible, when the solution is smooth.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] However, there are no known three-dimensional single-domain spectral shock capturing results (shock waves are not smooth).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] In the finite-element community, a method where the degree of the elements is very high or increases as the grid parameter *h* increases is sometimes called a spectral-element method.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Spectral methods can be used to solve differential equations (PDEs, ODEs, eigenvalue, etc) and optimization problems.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] When applying spectral methods to time-dependent PDEs, the solution is typically written as a sum of basis functions with time-dependent coefficients; substituting this in the PDE yields a system of ODEs in the coefficients which can be solved using any numerical method for ODEs.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Eigenvalue problems for ODEs are similarly converted to matrix eigenvalue problems .
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] The implementation of the spectral method is normally accomplished either with collocation or a Galerkin or a Tau approach .
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] For very small problems, the spectral method is unique in that solutions may be written out symbolically, yielding a practical alternative to series solutions for differential equations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Spectral methods can be computationally less expensive and easier to implement than finite element methods; they shine best when high accuracy is sought in simple domains with smooth solutions.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] However, because of their global nature, the matrices associated with step computation are dense and computational efficiency will quickly suffer when there are many degrees of freedom (with some exceptions, for example if matrix applications can be written as Fourier transforms).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] For larger problems and nonsmooth solutions, finite elements will generally work better due to sparse matrices and better modelling of discontinuities and sharp bends.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Here we presume an understanding of basic multivariate calculus and Fourier series.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] where the expression on the left denotes the second partial derivatives of *f* in *x* and *y*, respectively.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] This is the Poisson equation, and can be physically interpreted as some sort of heat conduction problem, or a problem in potential theory, among other possibilities.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] We have exchanged partial differentiation with an infinite sum, which is legitimate if we assume for instance that *f* has a continuous second derivative.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] which is an explicit formula for the Fourier coefficients *a**j*,*k*.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] With periodic boundary conditions, the Poisson equation possesses a solution only if *b*0,0 = 0.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Therefore, we can freely choose *a*0,0 which will be equal to the mean of the resolution.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] This corresponds to choosing the integration constant.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] To turn this into an algorithm, only finitely many frequencies are solved for.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] This introduces an error which can be shown to be proportional to $h^{n}$ , where $h:=1/n$ and n is the highest frequency treated.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Compute the Fourier transform (*a**j*,*k*) of *f* via the formula (*****).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Compute *f* by taking an inverse Fourier transform of (*aj,k*).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Since we're only interested in a finite window of frequencies (of size *n*, say) this can be done using a fast Fourier transform algorithm.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Therefore, globally the algorithm runs in time *O*(*n* log *n*).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] We wish to solve the forced, transient, nonlinear Burgers' equation using a spectral approach.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] The nonlinear term is a convolution, and there are several transform-based techniques for evaluating it efficiently.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] See the references by Boyd and Canuto et al. for more details.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] One can show that if g is infinitely differentiable, then the numerical algorithm using Fast Fourier Transforms will converge faster than any polynomial in the grid size h.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] That is, for any n>0, there is a $C_{n}<\infty$ such that the error is less than $C_{n}h^{n}$ for all sufficiently small values of h .
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] We say that the spectral method is of order n , for every n>0.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] Because a spectral element method is a finite element method of very high order, there is a similarity in the convergence properties.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/spectral-method] However, whereas the spectral method is based on the eigendecomposition of the particular boundary value problem, the finite element method does not use that information and works for arbitrary elliptic boundary value problems.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Weather forecasts are made by collecting quantitative data about the current state of the atmosphere, land, and ocean and using meteorology to project how the atmosphere will change at a given place.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Once calculated manually based mainly upon changes in barometric pressure, current weather conditions, and sky conditions or cloud cover, weather forecasting now relies on computer-based models that take many atmospheric factors into account.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Human input is still required to pick the best possible model to base the forecast upon, which involves pattern recognition skills, teleconnections, knowledge of model performance, and knowledge of model biases.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Hence, forecasts become less accurate as the difference between the current time and the time for which the forecast is being made (the *range* of the forecast) increases.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The use of ensembles and model consensus helps narrow the error and provide confidence in the forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] There is a wide variety of end uses for weather forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Weather warnings are important because they are used to protect lives and property.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Forecasts based on temperature and precipitation are important to agriculture, and therefore to traders within commodity markets.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Temperature forecasts are used by utility companies to estimate demand over the coming days.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] On an everyday basis, many people use weather forecasts to determine what to wear on a given day.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Since outdoor activities are severely curtailed by heavy rain, snow and wind chill, forecasts can be used to plan activities around these events, and to plan ahead and survive them.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Weather forecasting is a part of the economy.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] For example, in 2009, the US spent approximately $5.8 billion on it, producing benefits estimated at six times as much.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In 650 BC, the Babylonians predicted the weather from cloud patterns as well as astrology.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In about 350 BC, Aristotle described weather patterns in *Meteorologica*.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Later, Theophrastus compiled a book on weather forecasting, called the *Book of Signs*.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Chinese weather prediction lore extends at least as far back as 300 BC, which was also around the same time ancient Indian astronomers developed weather-prediction methods.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Ancient weather forecasting methods usually relied on observed patterns of events, also termed pattern recognition.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] For example, it was observed that if the sunset was particularly red, the following day often brought fair weather.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] This experience accumulated over the generations to produce weather lore.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] However, not all of these predictions prove reliable, and many of them have since been found not to stand up to rigorous statistical testing.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] It was not until the invention of the electric telegraph in 1835 that the modern age of weather forecasting began.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Before that, the fastest that distant weather reports could travel was around 160 kilometres per day (100 mi/d), but was more typically 60–120 kilometres per day (40–75 mi/day) (whether by land or by sea).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] By the late 1840s, the telegraph allowed reports of weather conditions from a wide area to be received almost instantaneously, allowing forecasts to be made from knowledge of weather conditions further upwind.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The two men credited with the birth of forecasting as a science were an officer of the Royal Navy Francis Beaufort and his protégé Robert FitzRoy.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Both were influential men in British naval and governmental circles, and though ridiculed in the press at the time, their work gained scientific credence, was accepted by the Royal Navy, and formed the basis for all of today's weather forecasting knowledge.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Beaufort developed the Wind Force Scale and Weather Notation coding, which he was to use in his journals for the remainder of his life.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] He also promoted the development of reliable tide tables around British shores, and with his friend William Whewell, expanded weather record-keeping at 200 British coast guard stations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Robert FitzRoy was appointed in 1854 as chief of a new department within the Board of Trade to deal with the collection of weather data at sea as a service to mariners.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] This was the forerunner of the modern Meteorological Office.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] All ship captains were tasked with collating data on the weather and computing it, with the use of tested instruments that were loaned for this purpose.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] A storm in October 1859 that caused the loss of the *Royal Charter* inspired FitzRoy to develop charts to allow predictions to be made, which he called "forecasting the weather", thus coining the term "weather forecast".
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Fifteen land stations were established to use the telegraph to transmit to him daily reports of weather at set times leading to the first gale warning service.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] His warning service for shipping was initiated in February 1861, with the use of telegraph communications.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The first daily weather forecasts were published in *The Times* in 1861.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In the following year a system was introduced of hoisting storm warning cones at the principal ports when a gale was expected.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The *"Weather Book"* which FitzRoy published in 1863 was far in advance of the scientific opinion of the time.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] As the electric telegraph network expanded, allowing for the more rapid dissemination of warnings, a national observational network was developed, which could then be used to provide synoptic analyses.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] To shorten detailed weather reports into more affordable telegrams, senders encoded weather information in telegraphic code, such as the one developed by the U.S.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Instruments to continuously record variations in meteorological parameters using photography were supplied to the observing stations from Kew Observatory – these cameras had been invented by Francis Ronalds in 1845 and his barograph had earlier been used by FitzRoy.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] To convey accurate information, it soon became necessary to have a standard vocabulary describing clouds; this was achieved by means of a series of classifications first achieved by Luke Howard in 1802, and standardized in the *International Cloud Atlas* of 1896.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] It was not until the 20th century that advances in the understanding of atmospheric physics led to the foundation of modern numerical weather prediction.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In 1922, English scientist Lewis Fry Richardson published "Weather Prediction By Numerical Process", after finding notes and derivations he worked on as an ambulance driver in World War I.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] He described therein how small terms in the prognostic fluid dynamics equations governing atmospheric flow could be neglected, and a finite differencing scheme in time and space could be devised, to allow numerical prediction solutions to be found.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Richardson envisioned a large auditorium of thousands of people performing the calculations and passing them to others.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] However, the sheer number of calculations required was too large to be completed without the use of computers, and the size of the grid and time steps led to unrealistic results in deepening systems.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] It was later found, through numerical analysis, that this was due to numerical instability.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The first computerised weather forecast was performed by a team composed of American meteorologists Jule Charney, Philip Duncan Thompson, Larry Gates, and Norwegian meteorologist Ragnar Fjørtoft, applied mathematician John von Neumann, and ENIAC programmer Klara Dan von Neumann.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Practical use of numerical weather prediction began in 1955, spurred by the development of programmable electronic computers.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The first-ever daily weather forecasts were published in *The Times* on August 1, 1861, and the first weather maps were produced later in the same year.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In 1911, the Met Office began issuing the first marine weather forecasts via radio transmission.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] These included gale and storm warnings for areas around Great Britain.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In the United States, the first public radio forecasts were made in 1925 by Edward B.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] "E.B." Rideout, on WEEI, the Edison Electric Illuminating station in Boston.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Weather Bureau, as did WBZ weather forecaster G.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The world's first televised weather forecasts, including the use of weather maps, were experimentally broadcast by the BBC in November 1936.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] This was brought into practice in 1949, after World War II.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] George Cowling gave the first weather forecast while being televised in front of the map in 1954.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In America, experimental television forecasts were made by James C.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Fidler in Cincinnati in either 1940 or 1947 on the DuMont Television Network.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In the late 1970s and early 1980s, John Coleman, the first weatherman for the American Broadcasting Company (ABC)'s *Good Morning America*, pioneered the use of on-screen weather satellite data and computer graphics for television forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In 1982, Coleman partnered with Landmark Communications CEO Frank Batten to launch The Weather Channel (TWC), a 24-hour cable network devoted to national and local weather reports.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Some weather channels have started broadcasting on live streaming platforms such as YouTube to reach more viewers.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The basic idea of numerical weather prediction is to sample the state of the fluid at a given time and use the equations of fluid dynamics and thermodynamics to estimate the state of the fluid at some time in the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The main inputs from country-based weather services are surface observations from automated weather stations at ground level over land and from weather buoys at sea.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Sites launch radiosondes, which rise through the depth of the troposphere and well into the stratosphere.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Data from weather satellites are used in areas where traditional data sources are not available.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Compared with similar data from radiosondes, the satellite data has the advantage of global coverage, but at a lower accuracy and resolution.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Meteorological radar provides information on precipitation location and intensity, which can be used to estimate precipitation accumulations over time.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Additionally, if a pulse Doppler weather radar is used then wind speed and direction can be determined.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] These methods, however, leave an in-situ observational gap in the lower atmosphere (from 100 m to 6 km above ground level).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] To reduce this gap, in the late 1990s weather drones started to be considered for obtaining data from those altitudes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Research has been growing significantly since the 2010s, and weather-drone data may in the future be added to numerical weather models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Commerce provides pilot reports along aircraft routes, and ship reports along shipping routes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Research flights using reconnaissance aircraft fly in and around weather systems of interest such as tropical cyclones.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Reconnaissance aircraft are also flown over the open oceans during the cold season into systems that cause significant uncertainty in forecast guidance, or are expected to be of high impact three–seven days into the future over the downstream continent.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Models are *initialized* using this observed data.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The irregularly spaced observations are processed by data assimilation and objective analysis methods, which perform quality control and obtain values at locations usable by the model's mathematical algorithms (usually an evenly spaced grid).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Commonly, the set of equations used to predict the physics and dynamics of the atmosphere is called primitive equations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] These are initialized from the analysis data and rates of change are determined.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The rates of change predict the state of the atmosphere a short time into the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The equations are then applied to this new atmospheric state to find new rates of change, which predict the atmosphere at a yet further time into the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] This *time stepping* procedure is continually repeated until the solution reaches the desired forecast time.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The Met Office's Unified Model is run six days into the future, the European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts model is run out to 10 days into the future, while the Global Forecast System model run by the Environmental Modeling Center is run 16 days into the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The raw output is often modified before being presented as the forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] This can be in the form of statistical techniques to remove known biases in the model, or of adjustments to take into account consensus among other numerical weather forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] MOS or model output statistics is a technique used to interpret numerical model output and produce site-specific guidance.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] This guidance is presented in coded numerical form and can be obtained for nearly all National Weather Service reporting stations in the United States.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] As proposed by Edward Lorenz in 1963, long-range forecasts, those made at a range of two weeks or more cannot definitively predict the state of the atmosphere, owing to the chaotic nature of the fluid dynamics equations involved.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In numerical models, extremely small errors in initial values double roughly every five days for variables such as temperature and wind velocity.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Essentially, a model is a computer program that produces meteorological information for future times at given locations and altitudes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] These equations—along with the ideal gas law—are used to evolve the density, pressure, and potential temperature scalar fields and the velocity vector field of the atmosphere through time.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Additional transport equations for pollutants and other aerosols are included in some primitive-equation mesoscale models as well.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The equations used are nonlinear partial differential equations, which are impossible to solve exactly through analytical methods, except for a few idealized cases.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Different models use different solution methods: some global models use spectral methods for the horizontal dimensions and finite difference methods for the vertical dimension, while regional and other global models usually use finite-difference methods in all three dimensions.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The simplest method of forecasting the weather, persistence, relies upon today's conditions to forecast tomorrow's.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] This can be valid when the weather achieves a steady state, such as during the summer season in the tropics.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] This method strongly depends upon the presence of a stagnant weather pattern.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Therefore, when in a fluctuating pattern, it becomes inaccurate.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] It can be useful in both short- and long-range forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Measurements of barometric pressure and the pressure tendency (the change of pressure over time) have been used in forecasting since the late 19th century.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The larger the change in pressure, especially if more than 3.5 hPa (2.6 mmHg), the larger the change in weather can be expected.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] If the pressure drop is rapid, a low pressure system is approaching, and there is a greater chance of rain.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Rapid pressure rises are associated with improving weather conditions, such as clearing skies.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Along with pressure tendency, the condition of the sky is one of the more important parameters used to forecast weather in mountainous areas.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Thickening of cloud cover or the invasion of a higher cloud deck is indicative of rain in the near future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] High thin cirrostratus clouds can create halos around the sun or moon, which indicates an approach of a warm front and its associated rain.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Morning fog portends fair conditions, as rainy conditions are preceded by wind or clouds that prevent fog formation.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The approach of a line of thunderstorms could indicate the approach of a cold front.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Cloud-free skies are indicative of fair weather for the near future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] A bar can indicate a coming tropical cyclone.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The use of sky cover in weather prediction has led to various weather lore over the centuries.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The forecasting of the weather for the following six hours is often referred to as nowcasting.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In this time range it is possible to forecast smaller features such as individual showers and thunderstorms with reasonable accuracy, as well as other features too small to be resolved by a computer model.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] A human given the latest radar, satellite and observational data will be able to make a better analysis of the small-scale features present and so will be able to make a more accurate forecast for the following few hours.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] However, there are now expert systems using those data and mesoscale numerical models to make better extrapolation, including the evolution of those features in time.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Accuweather is known for a Minute-Cast, which is a minute-by-minute precipitation forecast for the next two hours.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In the past, human forecasters were responsible for generating the weather forecast based upon available observations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Today, human input is generally confined to choosing a model based on various parameters, such as model biases and performance.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Using a consensus of forecast models, as well as ensemble members of the various models, can help reduce forecast error.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] However, regardless of how small the average error becomes with any individual system, large errors within any particular piece of guidance are still possible on any given model run.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Humans are required to interpret the model data into weather forecasts that are understandable to the end user.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Humans can use knowledge of local effects that may be too small in size to be resolved by the model to add information to the forecast.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] While increasing the accuracy of forecasting models implies that humans may no longer be needed in the forecasting process at some point in the future, there is currently still a need for human intervention.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The analog technique is a complex way of making a forecast, requiring the forecaster to remember a previous weather event that is expected to be mimicked by an upcoming event.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] What makes it a difficult technique to use is that there is rarely a perfect analog for an event in the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Some call this type of forecasting pattern recognition.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] It remains a useful method of observing rainfall over data voids such as oceans, as well as the forecasting of precipitation amounts and distribution in the future.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] A similar technique is used in medium-range forecasting, which is known as teleconnections, when systems in other locations are used to help pin down the location of another system within the surrounding regime.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] An example of teleconnections are by using El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO) related phenomena.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Initial attempts to use artificial intelligence began in the 2010s.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Huawei's Pangu-Weather model, Google's GraphCast, WindBorne's WeatherMesh model, Nvidia's FourCastNet and Earth-2, Jua's EPT-family models, and the European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts' Artificial Intelligence/Integrated Forecasting System, or AIFS all appeared in 2022–2023.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In 2024, AIFS started to publish real-time forecasts, showing specific skill at predicting hurricane tracks, but lower-performing on the intensity changes of such storms relative to physics-based models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Such models use no physics-based atmosphere modeling or large language models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Instead, they learn purely from data such as the ECMWF re-analysis ERA5.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] These models typically require far less compute than physics-based models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Microsoft's Aurora system offers global 10-day weather and 5-day air pollution (CO 2, NO, NO 2, SO 2, O 3, and particulates) forecasts with claimed accuracy similar to physics-based models, but at orders-of-magnitude lower cost.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Aurora was trained on more than a million hours of data from six weather/climate models.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In 2024, a group of researchers at Google's DeepMind AI research laboratories published a paper in *Nature* to describe their machine-learning model, called GenCast, that is expected to produce more accurate forecasts than the best traditional weather forecasting systems.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In a study conducted using the AIFS, Lang et al.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] (2024) presented 30-day ensemble simulations of the Madden–Julian oscillation.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Most end users of forecasts are members of the general public.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Thunderstorms can create strong winds and dangerous lightning strikes that can lead to deaths, power outages, and widespread hail damage.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Heavy snow or rain can bring transportation and commerce to a standstill, as well as cause flooding in low-lying areas.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Excessive heat or cold waves can sicken or kill those with inadequate utilities, and droughts can impact water usage and destroy vegetation.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Several countries employ government agencies to provide forecasts and watches/warnings/advisories to the public to protect life and property and maintain commercial interests.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Knowledge of what the end user needs from a weather forecast must be taken into account to present the information in a useful and understandable way.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Examples include the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service (NWS) and Environment Canada's Meteorological Service (MSC).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Traditionally, newspaper, television, and radio have been the primary outlets for presenting weather forecast information to the public.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In addition, some cities had weather beacons.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Increasingly, the internet is being used due to the vast amount of specific information that can be found.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In all cases, these outlets update their forecasts on a regular basis.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] A major part of modern weather forecasting is the severe weather alerts and advisories that the national weather services issue in case severe or hazardous weather is expected.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] This is done to protect life and property.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Some of the most commonly known of severe weather advisories are the severe thunderstorm and tornado warning, as well as the severe thunderstorm and tornado watch.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Other forms of these advisories include winter weather, high wind, flood, tropical cyclone, and fog.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Severe weather advisories and alerts are broadcast through the media, including radio, using emergency systems such as the Emergency Alert System, which break into regular programming.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The low temperature forecast for the current day is calculated using the lowest temperature found between 7 pm that evening through 7 am the following morning.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] So, in short, today's forecasted low is most likely tomorrow's low temperature.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Because the aviation industry is especially sensitive to the weather, accurate weather forecasting is essential.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Fog or exceptionally low ceilings can prevent many aircraft from landing and taking off.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Turbulence and icing are also significant in-flight hazards.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Thunderstorms are a problem for all aircraft because of severe turbulence due to their updrafts and outflow boundaries, icing due to the heavy precipitation, as well as large hail, strong winds, and lightning, all of which can cause severe damage to an aircraft in flight.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Volcanic ash is also a significant problem for aviation, as aircraft can lose engine power within ash clouds.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] On a day-to-day basis airliners are routed to take advantage of the jet stream tailwind to improve fuel efficiency.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Aircrews are briefed prior to takeoff on the conditions to expect en route and at their destination.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Additionally, airports often change which runway is being used to take advantage of a headwind.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] This reduces the distance required for takeoff and eliminates potential crosswinds.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Commercial and recreational use of waterways can be limited significantly by wind direction and speed, wave periodicity and heights, tides, and precipitation.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] These factors can each influence the safety of marine transit.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Consequently, a variety of codes have been established to efficiently transmit detailed marine weather forecasts to vessel pilots via radio, for example the MAFOR (marine forecast).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Typical weather forecasts can be received at sea through the use of RTTY, Navtex and Radiofax.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Farmers rely on weather forecasts to decide what work to do on any particular day.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] For example, drying hay is only feasible in dry weather.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Prolonged periods of dryness can ruin cotton, wheat, and corn crops.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] While corn crops can be ruined by drought, their dried remains can be used as a cattle feed substitute in the form of silage.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Frosts and freezes play havoc with crops both during the spring and fall.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] For example, peach trees in full bloom can have their potential peach crop decimated by a spring freeze.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Orange groves can suffer significant damage during frosts and freezes, regardless of their timing.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Forecasting of wind, precipitation and humidity is essential for preventing and controlling wildfires.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Indices such as the Canadian Forest fire weather index, the American Haines Index (dropped from 2025), and the Australian Fire Danger Rating System, have been developed to predict the areas more at risk of fire from natural or human causes.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Conditions for the development of harmful insects can also be predicted by forecasting the weather.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Electricity and gas companies rely on weather forecasts to anticipate demand, which can be strongly affected by the weather.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] They use the quantity termed the degree day to determine how strong a use there will be (heating degree day) or cooling (cooling degree day).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] These quantities are based on a daily average temperature of 65 °F (18 °C).
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Cooler temperatures force heating degree days (one per degree Fahrenheit), while warmer temperatures force cooling degree days.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] In winter, severe cold weather can cause a surge in demand as people turn up their heating.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Similarly, in summer a surge in demand can be linked with the increased use of air conditioning systems in hot weather.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] By anticipating a surge in demand, utility companies can purchase additional supplies of power or natural gas before the price increases, or in some circumstances, supplies are restricted through the use of brownouts and blackouts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Increasingly, private companies pay for weather forecasts tailored to their needs so that they can increase their profits or avoid large losses.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] For example, supermarket chains may change the stocks on their shelves in anticipation of different consumer spending habits in different weather conditions.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Weather forecasts can be used to invest in the commodity market, such as futures in oranges, corn, soybeans, and oil.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] A mobile unit in the Royal Air Force, working with the Met Office, forecasts the weather for regions in which British and allied armed forces are deployed.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] A group based at Camp Bastion used to provide forecasts for the British armed forces in Afghanistan.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Similar to the private sector, military weather forecasters present weather conditions to the warfighter community.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Military weather forecasters provide pre-flight and in-flight weather briefs to pilots and provide real-time resource protection services for military installations.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Naval forecasters cover the waters and ship weather forecasts.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] The United States Navy provides a special service for itself and the rest of the federal government by issuing forecasts for tropical cyclones across the Pacific and Indian Oceans through its Joint Typhoon Warning Center.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Within the United States, the 557th Weather Wing provides weather forecasting for the Air Force and the Army.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] All four of the mentioned military branches have their initial enlisted meteorology technical training at Keesler Air Force Base.
[src:weather-forecasting-nwp/weather-forecasting] Military and civilian forecasters actively cooperate in analyzing, creating and critiquing weather forecast products.
